Use MAUI's **app lifecycle events** (`OnSleep` / `OnResume`) paired with `Preferences` for lightweight persistence:

**In `App.xaml.cs`** — wire up lifecycle events:

```csharp
protected override void OnSleep()
{
    // App going to background — notify the current page
    if (Current?.MainPage is NavigationPage nav
        && nav.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
    {
        page.SaveDraft();
    }
}

protected override void OnResume()
{
    if (Current?.MainPage is NavigationPage nav
        && nav.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
    {
        page.RestoreDraft();
    }
}
```

**In `NotePage.xaml.cs`** — save/restore the draft:

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        RestoreDraft(); // also restore on first load
    }

    public void SaveDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    public void RestoreDraft()
    {
        if (Preferences.ContainsKey(DraftKey))
            NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    // Call this when the user explicitly saves/discards
    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| **Storage** | `Preferences` — ideal for small strings; for large notes use `SecureStorage` or a file |
| **OnSleep** | Fires when app is backgrounded or screen locks |
| **OnResume** | Fires when app returns to foreground |
| **Cleanup** | Call `ClearDraft()` after a successful save so stale drafts don't resurface |

> **Tip:** If your page uses data binding, save `ViewModel.DraftText` instead of reading the control directly — same lifecycle hooks apply.
